<TEXT>
the lower house of congress has 
temporarily suspended eight of twelve supreme court justices in a 
dispute over a beer tax aggravating political divisions in the 
country 
in response the justices threatened to annul the 1989 elections 
that put the current government in power they asked the armed 
forces to intervene 
the armed forces which have staged more than 100 coups in 
bolivias 165year history declined a statement said the conflict 
must be resolved according to the constitution 
the government had said two weeks ago that it would try eight 
out of the twelve justices for incompetence after they ruled that a 
beer tax authorized by congress was illegal 
charging the justices were influenced by beer companies the 
government said the repeal of the tax threatened an economic 
stabilization plan by depriving the treasury of 50 million 
the lower house temporarily suspended the justices on tuesday 
and the senate was to consider a measure permanently removing them 
the court responded by saying it would consider a petition 
presented in august 1989 by the revolutionary nationalist movement 
calling for the annulment of the elections the court is controlled 
by justices appointed under the previous revolutionary nationalist 
movement government 
congressmen tito hoz de vila head of the congressional economic 
committee said the conflict threatens the countrys political 
and economic stability 
it is necessary for bolivians to act with serenity said 
gen hugo banzer suarez a member of the governing coalition we 
must strengthen democracy which is in danger 
the revolutionary nationalist movement placed first in the 1989 
popular vote but lacked the required absolute majority as a 
result the president was elected by congress 
president jaime paz zamora of the revolutionary leftist 
movement finished third in the elections but was elected by 
congress through an alliance with the conservative nationalist 
democratic action party headed by former dictator banzer suarez 
whose party had finished second 
the opposition accused the governing coalition of attempting 
to destroy the judicial power by subjugating it to act as a legal 
office and not as a separate branch of government 
</TEXT>
