here are excerpts from tuesdays testimony 
before the senate ethics committee on the dealings five senators 
had with charles h keating jr owner of the failed lincoln 
savings and loan 
gwendolyn van paasschen economics assistant to sen john 
mccain rariz continued her testimony from monday she was 
questioned at one point by james hamilton the lawyer representing 
sen dennis deconcini dariz 
 
hamilton i would like to go back to the question i asked you 
before about whether sen mccain was coaxed into the meeting with 
four senators and edwin gray then chairman of the federal home 
loan bank board now who was coaxing sen mccain into this 
meeting 
van paasschen it was my view that what sen deconcini had 
suggested was inappropriate and i further went on to say that i 
believed that the reason that sen mccain was being involved in 
this was because sen mccain was a republican and that would 
ensure that it was a bipartisan effort and that keating had raised 
more for sen mccain than he had for sen deconcini at that time 
so if the press were to ever get a hold of it it would be more 
embarrassing for sen mccain than for sen deconcini 
hamilton what fact led you to believe that sen deconcini was 
coaxing sen mccain to this meeting because he was a republican 
 
van paasschen his demeanor was very persuasive he was coming 
to sen mccain instead of mr keating himself he was a democrat 
we were republican and as i said before keating had raised more 
for sen mccain than he had for sen deconcini at that time 
