<TEXT>
in the afternoon session any sabrin special assistant to 
special counsel robert bennett questioned sen mccains 
administrative aide christopher koch 
 
sabrin did you attend the meeting between mr keating and sen 
mccain on the 24th march 24 1987 
koch i did 
sabrin can you tell us with as much detail as you can recall 
what happened 
koch it would be a very difficult meeting to forget i 
remember vividly him mccain telling mr keating that he hadnt 
spent 5 years of his life in a prisoner of war camp to have his 
courage or his integrity questioned and he gave mr keating a 
dressing down the likes of which i in my experience on the hill 
had never experienced a senator giving a major employer of his 
state it was startling to me i mean it was a very vivid 
impression 
sabrin can you recall with any detail what the substance was of 
what mr keating was asking sen mccain to do and what his response 
was 
koch yes john said that theres certain things he can do and 
theres certain things he couldnt do he said he could find out if 
mr keatings allegations had merit he could look in and ask 
questions about if this investigation was taking so long why it 
was taking so long 
but he said i cant go in and do your bidding for you i 
cant go in and break arms and legs for you i can find out if 
youre being treated fairly 
mr keating thought he was being treated very very 
unfairly it was almost as if he hadnt been listening to john 
because he again got into requests for him to get involved and 
again the meeting got a little bit hot and john came back at him 
again and said he couldnt do that 
sabrin what was your understanding after mr keating walked 
out of sen mccains office of how the whole matter was left 
koch i thought that the relationship had clearly in my opinion 
come to a screeching halt i had never heard two people have 
that kind of conversation and ever want to talk to each other 
again 
