<TEXT>
president bush counseled just be patient when 
pressed on why the soviet union hadnt joined his call for a 
resolution authorizing military force against kuwait but in the 
end bush may have been the impatient one 
by seeking support for a resolution dealing with war at a 
conference dedicated to peace bush may have given the impression 
of pushing too hard that threatened to alienate some of those who 
stood with the united states in earlier united nations actions 
against international outlaw iraq 
the presidents hand on the persian gulf also may have been 
weakened by the political defeat delivered to british prime 
minister margaret thatcher on tuesday by her own conservative 
party mrs thatcher who was forced into a second party leadership 
vote next week has been bushs staunchest ally in insisting that 
the military option be left open in the gulf 
bush was heading to the middle east where he will meet with 
saudi and exiled kuwaiti officials today us forces on 
thanksgiving and egyptian officials on friday without the 
consensus he had hoped to forge in paris 
but not for lack of trying 
like lobbyists on capitol hill in search of votes bush and 
secretary of state james a baker iii worked the halls and the 
elegant salons in which the 34nation conference on cooperation and 
security in europe had gathered to celebrate the end of eastwest 
hostilities 
but the us efforts failed to wring agreement from summit 
leaders on what to do next to dislodge iraqs saddam hussein from 
kuwait 
when the summit leaders went into a closeddoor session tuesday 
for concluding discussions the crisis in the persian gulf didnt 
even come up participants said 
after bushs private dinner with soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachev on monday night failed to produce a breakthrough baker 
continued to press the presidents case during two meetings tuesday 
with soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze 
speaking with reporters after the second meeting shevardnadze 
stressed past ussoviet cooperation on the gulf he noted it was 
remarkable considering the long history of rivalries 
that unity and high level of solidarity that has been 
accomplished in the course of preparation and adoption of past 
security council resolutions is something that we cherish very 
much he said 
so please dont make me get ahead of time he added 
the soviets did agree that the united nations should take 
another look at the effectiveness of the sanctions it imposed on 
iraq with an eye to new resolutions if necessary to enforce 
the old ones 
that narrowed the gap a little bit but administration officials 
