<TEXT>
black workers at the treasury department 
agency that produces dollars stamps and government securities will 
be given more opportunity for advancement under a court settlement 
that also provides for 14 million in back pay 
the settlement was announced tuesday by lawyers who brought the 
action and was confirmed by the bureau of engraving and printing 
the bureau said it initiated the settlement and was pleased with 
its terms 
the agreement in us district court covers 248 present and 
former employees of the bureau it ends an 8yearold lawsuit in 
which black workers contended they were denied access to 
higherpaying craft jobs such as bookbinders printers or 
pressmen 
the bureau employs 750 craft workers and 1750 noncraft 
workers said bureau spokesman ira polikoff 
the lawsuit said the bureau perpetuated an oldboy network under 
which white workers were brought in from private industry by 
friends and relatives and were given preferential treatment for 
craft jobs 
whites held 85 percent of the craft jobs while blacks held 
nearly 100 percent of the noncraft jobs the plaintiffs argued 
blacks were held back by an apprenticeship system and written 
tests that had nothing to do with the skills required for the 
better jobs the plaintiffs claimed they added that blacks often 
had to train the whites on equipment that was unique to the bureau 
the settlement suspends the writtentest requirement for 
selecting apprentices to the craft jobs and shortens the 
apprenticeship period the agreement also sets aside 72 bookbinder 
and pressman apprenticeships to be filled from within the bureau 
top officials of the bureau of engraving and printing just 
didnt seem to care about the discrimination built into the 
hiring and apprenticeship system said attorney david p donovan 
joseph m sellers of the washington lawyers committee for civil 
rights under law called the situation at the bureau one of the 
most egregious examples of discrimination in the federal 
government 
polikoff said the bureau initiated the settlement which 
includes reforms suggested by peter daly after he took over as 
bureau director in 1988 
he saw that the system was outdated and that it needed to be 
modernized polikoff said he disagreed with sellers 
characterization of the degree of discrimination and said that in 
1983 the bookbinders apprentices consisted of 17 blacks and one 
woman 
the settlement also provides for wage increases for 39 employees 
costing 300000 in the first year of the settlement and pension 
increases for 44 retired employees at a cost of more than 170000 
a year according to a statement from the washington law firm of 
wilmer cutler amp pickering whose attorneys brought the lawsuit 
