<DOCNO> AP901121-0065 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
shogun the musical certainly has the 
spectacle what it needs is a coherent story a few good songs and 
a couple of characters you could care about 
all are missing from this big beached whale of a show that 
floated belly up into broadways marquis theater on tuesday night 
the premiere was postponed several days after the leading man 
philip casnoff was bonked by a piece of falling scenery during a 
preview performance nov 13 
its amazing casnoff wasnt hurt before the show opens with a 
shipwreck a rather nifty maritime catastrophe done with an 
honesttogoodness ship laser beams and some blackclad sea 
sprites pulling billowing sheets of cloth the musical also has an 
earthquake and several big battle scenes including one striking 
chorus line of warriors on horseback they are not enough 
although shogun has the technical expertise of recent big 
british musical blockbusters it doesnt have the emotional sweep 
of les miserables or the sense of romance and fun found in 
the phantom of the opera director michael smuin has mastered 
the wizardry of modern stage technology but he cant do much with a 
baffling narrative and pedestrian music and lyrics 
the musical is based on james clavells mammoth novel of 
17thcentury japan the book is so detailed and complicated the 
paperback version runs more than 1200 pages that any adaptation 
is bound to be more outline than story even so the producers have 
included a twopage plot synopsis and a glossary of japanese 
phrases that still dont make the tale completely accessible 
shogun concerns an englishman john blackthorne shipwrecked 
on the japanese coast he gets involved with several warlords a 
conniving portuguese jesuit and most significantly the lovely 
lady mariko who happens to be married to a nobleman you know 
there will be trouble 
shogun takes itself very seriously the characters dont 
talk they proclaim when they are not proclaiming they are 
explaining the plot adapter john driver uses several of the main 
characters to summarize what is going on its like listening to 
cliffs notes read out loud 
when they are not explaining the performers are singing 
composer paul chiharas wallpaperthin music melodies that linger 
no longer than the time it takes to sing them the music and 
lyrics which are by driver often seem unnecessary stopping the 
plot rather than advancing it and more important in the love 
songs failing to forge the bond between blackthorne and mariko 
instead these love songs are so generic particularly an often 
repeated number called born to be together that they probably 
could be dropped into any musical and work ok 
the cast doesnt let the weak material stop them casnoff is 
personable a handsome leading man who sings with authority and 
even seems to have a sense of humor june angela as the doomed 
mariko is striking a lovely singer who throws herself into the 
show with even more conviction 
the rotund francis ruivivar as the good warlord is stuck with 
a character who alternates between buffoon and nobleman he also 
has one of the shows more pointless songs rum below in which 
blackthorne teaches the wouldbe shogun to dance a jig but the 
shows campiest moment occurs early in the second act when the 
geishas sing about oriental sexual toys truly embarrassing 
the costumes by patricia zipprodt are extraordinary an endless 
display of patterned silks and brocades as well as a parade of 
armor for scores of warriors no one seems to wear the same outfit 
twice loren shermans settings are equally lavish particularly 
the richly decorated darkhued osaka castle lair of the evil lord 
ishido the lighting by natasha katz beautifully shows off the 
settings and the costumes 
but these design achievements cant really mask the thinness of 
what were seeing and hearing on stage shogun the musical can 
occasionally dazzle the eye but it never touches the heart and 
mind 
what other critics said 
frank rich in the new york times said casnoffs accident with 
the scenery may have been the biggest break of his career 
because his performance after his recovery had the swaggering 
selfassurance of a star in complete command of a vast 
production 
clive barnes in the new york post said the show is as 
unremittingly serious as triviality can ever hope to be the 
book is unwieldy and the lyrics banal he said 
linda winer in newsday said shogun is drivel but its not 
inept drivel without cameron mackintosh and his presold 
international marketing machine behind it however the show will 
need all the karma it can get 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

