<TEXT>
boris n yeltsin today criticized soviet president 
mikhail s gorbachevs plans to strengthen the executive branch of 
government as illogical and hastily prepared 
yeltsin president of largest soviet republic said russia could 
not be forced into signing gorbachevs proposed union treaty which 
would redefine the relationship between the 15 republics and the 
national government 
the treaty would be signed only if russias real sovereignty 
would be assured and if issues are resolved over the ownership of 
the vast republics bounty of gold diamonds oil gas and other 
natural resources said yeltsin gorbachevs frequent critic and 
main political rival 
gorbachev on saturday proposed dumping his embattled prime 
minister nikolai i ryzhkov and revamping the executive branch to 
put it entirely under presidential control the supreme soviet 
legislature gave the proposals initial approval but is expected to 
consider them further friday 
the soviet leader made the proposals after the supreme soviet 
urged him to resolve a building political crisis that was 
paralyzing efforts at reforming the nations economy 
most of the 15 soviet republics including russia have declared 
some form of sovereignty pushing for local control over their own 
economies political structures and culture this has resulted in 
political confrontations with the central government over which 
directives should be carried out or ignored 
yeltsin speaking to reporters at the opening of a historical 
exhibition at the russian republics headquarters said gorbachevs 
proposed strengthening of the national presidency seemed to be 
prepared in a hurry probably as a result of the debates in the 
supreme soviet or prompted by the staff of the supreme soviet or 
presidential aides 
but they are not exactly logical not quite consistent for 
one thing and for another such things should be discussed and 
adopted taking into account the will of the republics he said 
without elaboration 
yeltsin who on monday urged a referendum on the entire 
presidential system and the governments performance said today 
that a decision on such a vote hasnt been made and he would not 
predict one 
asked if gorbachevs reputation or credibility are helped by the 
proposal to strengthen his presidential powers yeltsin replied 
it was my impression from the stormy meetings in the ukraine 
where i spent only one day that no it doesnt 
yeltsin was in the ukraine earlier this week to sign a treaty on 
relations between that republic and the russian republic 
</TEXT>
