<TEXT>
nov 15 
the times of india on japan 
important winds of change are blowing over japan today with the 
accession to the throne of the new emperor akihito the resurgence 
of japanese militarism which historically has been associated with 
royalist rule has again become an issue 
mr kaifu favours the participation of a japanese military 
contingent in the gulf alongside western partners he has been 
pressured to adopt this view by the us but it is clear that tokyo 
itself has fewer reservations than ever before about flexing its 
longdormant military muscle just as emperor akihitos 
accession to what is seen as divine status is a generational change 
at the apex it may be only a short while before a new japanese 
generation with only faint memories of world war ii or the earlier 
interwar period feels that the resurgence of japanese militarism 
is but the natural complement of its exceptional economic 
might 
 
nov 14 
the herald of harare zimbabwe on the gulf crisis 
war is now inevitable in the persian gulf if only because the 
foreign forces have to seek justification for having been deployed 
there in the first place 
president george bush whose country already has the largest 
single foreign force in the gulf has just ordered a further 
buildup 
two weeks ago the americans and the saudis streamlined the chain 
of command of their forces should war break out with iraq many saw 
this as one more step in the direction of armed confrontation 
the american administration is under severe pressure at home to 
do something now before the all too familiar campaign to bring 
our boys back home gains momentum 
mr bush smarting from a midterm election disaster now has the 
time to devote his energy to the gulf crisis but he and president 
saddam hussein more than anybody else have burned their bridges 
in a diplomatic game whose end result has all the potential for a 
devastating conflict 
 
nov 16 
el pais of madrid on the first anniversary of the murder of 
jesuit priests in el salvador 
the military chiefs who planned and ordered the action dont 
even appear as suspects the judge handling the case has been and 
remains incapable of sitting all those responsible in the dock 
the blame lies with among others the government of the extreme 
rightist president alfredo cristiani which far from fulfilling its 
promise to solve the crime has dragged its feet and even put 
stumbling blocks in the way of the judicial investigation 
the scandal is of such magnitude that the government of the 
united states has reduced its military aid to el salvador by 50 
percent other governments like the government of spain less 
able to impose material sanctions have put considerable moral 
pressure on the central american nation without much success 
either 
in the end it is not so much a question of finding and 
punishing those guilty of a repulsive crime as it is of a country 
demonstrating that it is capable of functioning like a civilized 
society that follows the rule of law 
 
nov 19 
financial times of london on the soviet union 
the soviet crisis deepens by the day hunger possibly 
famine is facing the soviet union as the snows of winter cover 
fields of rotting crops oil production is falling sharply and 
the problem of delivering oil and gas is compounded by 
disintegrating pipelines and a chaotic transport system what 
we are witnessing is the accelerating collapse of political and 
economic structures this is happening in a country where the 
destruction of civil society over 70 years has fatally weakened the 
countrys capacity to react creatively to the new freedoms suddenly 
granted it all that is clear at this stage is that the 
transition from communism is going to be much longer much harder 
and much more expensive than imagined over a year ago to achieve 
it peacefully could cost the west as much effort and treasure as 
the cold war whose demise we celebrate in paris this week this is 
the probable scale of the challenge ahead 
</TEXT>
