geneva that he had been satisfied with the talks on a possible 
political solution to the afghan conflict 
a cornerstone has been laid for opening talks and dialogue and 
for advancing the process as well as the implementation of the 
peace process najibullah said no doubt it will bear fruit 
najibullah later left for the swiss capital in bern where he was 
to meet with swiss legislators one deputy gilles petitpierre 
said plans for an afghanistan peace conference hosted by 
switzerland was a likely topic 
at a news conference najibullah did not say when the talks took 
place he also declined to identify the afghan resistance leaders 
with whom he met saying only they were prominent personalities 
of the opposition side 
some observers speculated that najibullah met in geneva with pir 
sayed ahmed gailani leader of the national islamic front the 
most moderate of the seven afghan rebel groups allied against the 
