san salvador nor to most of eastern el salvador 
the farabundo marti national liberation front the rebel 
organization also known as fmln denied it had launched an 
offensive it said the attacks aimed to prod cristianis government 
back to the negotiating table 
government and rebel representatives have held five rounds of 
talks since may negotiations were to resume nov 4 in mexico but 
bogged down over bitterly differing positions on the future role of 
the armed forces it is time to say enough to the fmln this 
cannot be called military action since most of those affected are 
civilians cristiani said in a radiotv speech late tuesday 
its a new terrorist offensive 
the only thing these actions do is endanger the negotiating 
process since violence engenders violence and will not provide the 
flexible and rational conditions needed to end the bloodshed he 
added 
more than 73000 people have been killed nearly half of them 
civilians since the civil war began in october 1979 many have 
been slain by death squads linked to the military who suspected 
them of leftist sympathies 
the rebels say they are willing to demobilize and join the 
political process only if the current armed forces are disbanded a 
demand the government refuses to entertain 
congress has slashed el salvadors 85 million annual military 
aid in half for 1991 to prod the negotiations along it stipulated 
that aid would be restored if the rebels launched an offensive and 
cut off altogether if the cristiani government balked at further 
talks 
a rebel communique shortly after the attacks were launched said 
the fmln could launch an allout offensive if the government does 
not return to the negotiating table soon 
fmlns action followed the first anniversary of the armys 
massacre of six jesuit priests their housekeeper and her teenage 
daughter on nov 16 1989 during a rebel offensive in the capital 
the guerrillas international human rights groups and us 
congressional investigators say the armed forces murder and torture 
political opponents and are corrupt 
defense minister col rene emilio ponce warned in a radiotv 
message tuesday night the rebels were likely to intensify their 
attacks he said a total of 25 people were killed and 126 wounded 
in the fighting 
ponce said 12 government soldiers were killed and 76 wounded 
and 10 guerrillas were killed and an undetermined number injured 
he said civilian casualties amounted to three dead and 50 wounded 
a telephone survey of hospitals first aid centers military 
officers in the field and town officials provided the casualty 
figures earlier tuesday showing that at least 27 were killed and 
141 wounded 
one military airplane and three small civilian planes were 
destroyed by rebel gunfire at the main air base on the outskirts of 
the capital ponce said 
guerrilla sabotage damaged electrical installations and power 
lines affecting about twothirds of this central american nation of 
more than 55 million people the government electrical company 
said 
