<TEXT>
the us postal service and union leaders for 
660000 workers accused each other wednesday of intentionally 
botching contract talks so wage and job security disputes would go 
to arbitration 
the postal service never had any intention of entering into 
collective bargaining with the unions they kept us dangling never 
once did they get down to the crux of the issues said vincent 
sombrotto president of the 234000member national letter carriers 
association 
but postmaster general anthony m frank said it appeared union 
leaders were the ones who wanted a thirdparty involved because 
they waited until three days before tuesdays midnight deadline to 
propose a 50 billion pay increase package 
why three days ahead of time you would ask for a 50 billion 
increase its just so far off the wall it may well be a not very 
hidden signal that they want to go to arbitration frank said 
the contract dispute was sent to a lengthy binding arbitration 
process after three months of talks between the postal service and 
its four largest unions broke down 
the stalemate was not expected to create any disruption in mail 
service because it is illegal for postal workers to strike 
once an impasse is reached in postal talks federal law provides 
for the establishment of a factfinding commission under the 
direction of the federal mediation and conciliation service to 
review the dispute 
the factfinders will report within 45 days if management and 
labor still cant reach agreement an arbitration panel will settle 
the dispute the two sides could waive the factfinding step and 
move straight to arbitration to speed things up the process could 
take up to three months 
negotiators also could agree to resume bargaining and settle the 
dispute on their own 
key disputes were pay increases and how many parttime workers 
the postal service should be allowed to hire to help it shift to 
automation 
the postal service had offered workers automatic cash bonuses of 
950 over two years and additional performancebased bonuses of up 
to 1100 a year if certain customer satisfaction and budget goals 
were met 
unions seeking a threeyear contract asked for 8 percent pay 
increases the first year and 7 percent raises the next two years 
letter carriers and clerks make between 24000 and 31500 a year 
plus an additional 8500 in benefits 
the postal service said the unions 50 billion pay increase 
package would mean stamp prices would have to be increased from 25 
cents to 43 cents 
the service no longer subsidized by taxpayers must break even 
over time its board of governors already has proposed raising the 
cost of mailing a letter from 25 cents to 30 cents next spring 
regardless of what the contract includes 
in addition to the letter carriers and the postal workers the 
other unions involved are the national postal mail handlers union 
which represents 50000 mail handlers and the national rural 
letter carriers association with about 42000 members 
