<TEXT>
the state department reacted sharply wednesday 
to a military campaign launched by leftist rebels in el salvador 
and left open the possibility of increasing military aid to the 
salvadoran armed forces 
deputy spokesman richard boucher strongly condemned the military 
campaign by the fmln rebels accusing the insurgents of violating a 
commitment not to undertake military attacks that affect the 
civilian population 
he said seven civilians were killed and 67 wounded 
americas watch a private human rights group said the rebels 
have been responsible for only a small percentage of the civilian 
deaths in el salvador over the years ann manuel an associate at 
americas watch said the vast majority of the estimated 40000 
civilian killings have been the work of government forces and 
rightist death squads 
an fmln statement said tuesdays attacks were aimed at inducing 
the government to return to the negotiating table 
under legislation approved last month congress cut military aid 
to el salvador to 425 million half the administrations 
request president bush had objected strongly to the congressional 
action 
the legislation would allow the cut aid to be restored if the 
rebels launched a military offensive that threatens the government 
boucher said that provision of the legislation was being reviewed 
in light of tuesdays attacks 
the attacks he said did not appear to pose a threat to the 
governments survival 
other officials said preliminary consultations had begun with 
the staff of the chief sponsor of the legislation sen christopher 
dodd dconn dodd was out of the city wednesday 
the administration had argued forcefully against the aid 
cutback contending it didnt contain sufficient incentives for the 
fmln to agree to a ceasefire and to negotiate a settlement to 
their 10year war with the governent 
proponents of the cutback saw it as an inducement for the 
government to meet the rebels half way in peace talks that began 
earlier this year five rounds have been held since may 
an additional stipulation of the legislation is that all 
military aid to the armed forces would be cut off if the government 
refused to negotiate in good faith 
boucher said the government has made a number of concessions 
during the peace talks 
among other things he said the government has offered to 
transfer police forces to civilian control abolish civil defense 
units at the beginning of a ceasefire and disband immediate 
reaction battalions it also is committed to reducing the size of 
the armed forces by threefourths when a final settlement is 
reached he said 
boucher accused the fmln of cynicism by describing the attacks 
as a limited national campaign undertaken in the spirit of 
accelerating the negotiating process 
once again the fmln is talking about peace settlement while 
raining violence and death on el salvadors citizens the fmln has 
repeatedly stalled the negotiating process over the past four 
months and now claims to be seeking to accelerating it boucher 
said 
he said a us military helicopter was struck by gunfire during 
the attack one crewman suffered minor injuries from broken glass 
but the helicopter returned safely to its base 
