a federal judge has approved settlement of a 
classaction lawsuit that claimed state farm insurance companies 
discriminated against minorities and women in its texas region 
under the settlement approved tuesday by us district judge 
david hittner state farm will distribute 12 million it will go 
to the seven women who filed the lawsuit last year and to qualified 
hispanics blacks and women who were not hired recruited or 
promoted in agent or representative trainee jobs before 1984 
state farm also agreed to establish a fund for scholarships 
insurance training classes and recruitment of women and minorities 
company lawyers said in a statement that the settlement did not 
constitute an admission by state farm that it had violated title 
vii of the civil rights act of 1964 which prohibits employment 
discrimination on the basis of race color religion sex and 
national origin 
the lawsuit was filed by seven women who said they were 
unlawfully denied positions as state farm trainee agents and field 
claim representatives between 1975 and 1983 they had sought 100 
million in damages 
the equal employment opportunity commission joined in the 
lawsuit 
it accused state farm of reserving the jobs of sales agents 
claims adjusters and underwriters for white men at the time the 
895 agents in the companys texas region included 126 women and 125 
minorities 
state farms texas region headquartered in austin covered the 
southern half of texas including houston san antonio austin and 
el paso the remainder of state farms texas operations 
headquartered in dallas was not affected by the lawsuit 
in a similar case in california state farm agreed in 1988 to 
name women to half its sales agents jobs and pay millions of 
dollars to women who contended they were discriminated against from 
1974 to 1987 
that lawsuit accused state farm of refusing to recruit women on 
the same basis as men for agent jobs and discouraging women from 
applying for the lucrative jobs 
according to the lawsuit although 80 percent of all state farm 
employees in california were women 98 percent of its agents were 
men 
</TEXT>
