<TEXT>
the disorder is often misdiagnosed in adults and 
even when identified some physicians are reluctant to prescribe 
the proper medication speed and related stimulants it was 
discovered that the hyperactive child syndrome persisted into 
adulthood in 1971 but now scientists are upping the numbers for 
the adult population 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
up to seven million american adults may be 
suffering from a disorder they dont know they have it was first 
described in the medical literature in 1902 but its name is still 
being debated 
most of these adults know something is wrong but they dont 
know what says dr alan zametkin a psychiatrist at the national 
institutes of mental health 
best known as the hyperactive child syndrome the scientific 
name is attention deficit hyperactivity disorder residual type 
adhdrt when it persists into adulthood 
in 1971 dr paul wender of the university of utah a pioneer in 
the field recognized that it sometimes persisted into adulthood 
since then researchers have found increasing numbers of adults 
still suffering from the syndrome it is now estimated that 40 
percent to 60 percent of diagnosed childhood cases persist 
about 3 percent to 6 percent of all children are diagnosed with 
the disorder it is the most common reason for referrals to mental 
health specialists 
it is generally accepted that it affects five times more boys 
than girls but university of yale medical school pediatrician dr 
sally shaywitz believes girls are significantly undercounted 
it is the squeaky wheel that gets referred the child who 
appears motor driven cannot stay in his seat cannot concentrate 
cannot wait for his turn speaks out in classrooms has a short 
attention span an insatiable need for attention is very 
impulsive appears far too independent for his age has few social 
skills and frequently bullies other children 
twothirds of adhd children also suffer from a specific 
development disorder dyslexia being the most common 
those missed are often milder cases or very bright children who 
really may not have to concentrate children with no comorbidity 
and children who do not outwardly manifest the hyperactivity 
some adult cases especially those not diagnosed in childhood 
can be difficult to diagnose other psychiatric problems may 
accompany the disorder and physicians just arent looking for it 
the reason the diagnosis is often missed is that it is never 
even considered says dr ivan goldberg a new york city 
psychopharmacologist who treats adult cases 
one who agrees is dr barry garfinkel director of child and 
adolescent psychiatry at the university of minnesota and chairman 
of the committee that will seek to redefine and perhaps rename the 
disorder for the diagnostic and statistical manual dsm iv due 
out in 1993 
we trained doctors to believe adhd disappeared with 
adolescence the patients whom we didnt train are way ahead of the 
clinicians says dr garfinkel if you throw in a patient 
without the hyperactivity the physician for sure would be at a 
real loss in putting it all together 
the core of the disorder is the attention deficit not the 
hyperactivity despite its name the hyperactivity is the most 
dramatically recognizable symptom however there are cases where 
the hyperactivity is not present and the sufferer appears 
hypoactive scientists say only 10 percent lack hyperactivity 
the sad thing is that up to 85 percent can be helped with 
medication most sufferers feel isolated and alone not realizing 
they have so much company or that medication is available 
the disorder untreated can destroy lives some women who 
suspect something is wrong have chosen not to have children because 
they did not want to pass along this monster with no name others 
are working in jobs far beneath their intellectual abilities the 
prison population is probably rife with sufferers 
many adults retain traces of the hyperactivity but have learned 
to cope in such a way that it is not so evident but the attention 
deficit has not decreased 
zametkins research using a pet scan on 25 adhd adults and 50 
normal controls was the lead article in the prestigious new england 
journal of medicine on nov 15 an accompanying editorial by dr 
gabrielle weiss of montreal childrens hospital said the findings 
represent a clear advance in our understanding of 
hyperactivity 
zametkin found that the parts of the brain that control 
attention dont work as hard as normal brains it may be the best 
evidence yet that an abnormality in the brain is at the root of the 
problem 
im not going to say its the cause said zametkin but 
its possible this has something to do with the cause 
wender suggested that the cortex the higher part of the brain 
may be sluggish because of faulty control signals from a more 
primitive part of the brain 
dr c thomas gualtieri a neuro psychiatrist at the university 
of north carolina in chapel hill predicts that within five years 
pet scans will be able to diagnose the disorder 
that would certainly have helped one man blessed with 
extraordinary intellectual gifts he was hypoactive and guesses he 
saw 20 psychologists and psychiatrists before he got what is 
probably the correct diagnosis attention deficit disorder without 
hyperactivity 
he prefers to remain anonymous but describes his attention 
deficits 
i claw for every word in reading writing and speaking he 
says appearing laconic as he struggles for precisely the right 
word 
his brain fleet agile and retentive is cursed to move at the 
anguished gait of a tortoise to even touch his gifts requires 
herculean efforts and untold time 
ignorance here would indeed be bliss but that is not the 
reality 
</TEXT>
