<TEXT>
the great lakes huron erie ontario michigan and superior 
were for a period rich in history and lore the main american 
arteries of commerce 
timber to build cities floated down from the canadian shores 
iron ore to make steel sailed out of superior grain stone coal 
and copper filled cargo holds but the ships also carried human 
cargo and their belongings fur traders immigrants pioneers 
laborers homesteaders 
the wooden boats and steel freighters never were a match for the 
sudden fury of the inland seas where unexpected west winds in an 
afternoon can drive up waves three stories high 
the great storm of 1913 a sixday blow sank 10 ships and 
killed 235 seamen gales from 1878 to 1898 ravaged nearly 6000 
ships and sank more than 1000 of them 
modern ships have fared little better in 1964 a huron storm 
tore the ore freighter daniel j morell in half only one of its 
crew of 29 survived eleven years later the freighter edmund 
fitzgerald and its crew of 29 went down in superior seconds after 
the captain radioed that he was holding his own 
the great lakes have become an archaeologists paradise where 
the water is deep and cold decay is arrested and each wreck 
remains a frozen moment of history 
the preservation is so remarkable that bodies can last for 
years skeletons for centuries archaeologists excavating the wreck 
of the rockaway in lake michigan found the remains of salted meat 
in the galley and rope made from corn leaves still sitting in a pot 
used to mix caulking the schooner went down in 1891 
the sort of hollywood concept of what a shipwreck looks like 
actually exists in the great lakes said rockaway archaeologist 
ken pott from his museum in south haven mich short of a 
skeleton lashed to the wheel its all there 
for example the hamilton and the scourge two canadian 
battleships from the war of 1812 went down in 300 feet of water in 
lake ontario pott says a searcher using submersible cameras found 
the ship intact replete with cutlasses cannons guns bones and 
masts 
but the conservation work of maritime archaeologists such as 
pott is up against an army of black marketeers and souvenir 
seekers 
simple wood blocks that litter wrecks by the hundreds fetch 500 
in an antiques store collectors will pay 10000 for a ships bell 
or a wood steering wheel a carved ships figurehead is almost 
priceless 
such stripping was legal in michigan until 1980 when the state 
passed a law allowing salvage only under permit wisconsin only 
recently toughened its law all of the great lakes states and 
ontario outlaw stripping to some degree but some such as 
michigan are willing to grant salvage permits especially to 
divers picking up things for museums 
archaeological surveys take years the pillage can occur 
overnight witness the fate of the us coast guard cutter 
mesquite 
that crippled buoy tender was buried at sea last july dropped 
intact to the bottom of lake superior 
the stripping started immediately dinner plates from the boats 
galley tools from the work rooms hard hats from lockers dress 
jackets out of the closets of crew members 
i am appalled at what happened says michigan archaeologist 
john halsey in lansing it was like a feeding frenzy were 
talking in hours in days 
because of that many explorers go to great pains to hide their 
discoveries charles feltner an engineer for ford motor co found 
the 1856 wreck of the brig sandusky in the straits of mackinac he 
dove on it for years in secrecy then he made the find public 
people stripped the thing in a couple of months feltner 
says things like dishes tools all the blocks belaying pins 
deadeyes you name it 
the original ships rams head figurehead no longer remains 
divers bolted it back down after someone tried to steal it too 
wouldbe looters persisted until divers removed the original for 
preservation and last year installed a lookalike 
that was 10 years ago feltner thinks the advent of divers such 
as biniecki signals a change in ethic today feltner feels the 
looting would take years not months 
its still bad enough to where divers 25 years from now arent 
going to have much to look at feltner says the whole idea of 
seeing a virgin wreck will be gone 
</TEXT>
