<TEXT>
the numbers are black and white the reasons 
are decidedly gray 
in primetime television 91 percent of all directors are men 
of producers 85 percent are men of writers 75 percent are men 
a yearlong study titled whats wrong with this picture 
examined all 80 of last seasons primetime entertainment programs 
for their treatment of women both behind the camera and in front of 
it 
since its release by women in film and the washington dcbased 
national commission on working women the reports findings have 
been called shocking horrendous and bizarre by the few topranking 
females in the business but to ask why is to receive far more 
muted answers 
lynn loring the president of mgmpathe communications corps 
television division said discrimination is not easy to define 
i feel it more than see it loring said like when im in 
a room at an important meeting and theres 14 people at the 
conference table theres only one woman and thats me 
there is a boys club in television said loring and they play 
basketball together but i can outski all of them she added 
with characteristic dry wit im too short to play basketball 
lengthy interviews with some of the most powerful female 
television executives in hollywood produced a wide range of 
theories about why women are underrepresented in the tv industry 
the most common television mirrors society until there is 
equality for women in real life most of the women said there will 
be none for females in the makebelieve world of tv 
the second most common response i dont know 
of the women interviewed for this story not one said they had 
suffered sexual discrimination rather they said discrimination 
is so subtle and so far entrenched that it simply can be part of 
the landscape 
discrimination does not always mean a casting couch experience 
most of the time these women said it is insidious 
but betty friedan who helped launch the modern womens movement 
with her book the feminine mystique disagreed 
they may have never been told we wouldnt give you this show 
because youre a woman but theyre not giving shows to women the 
numbers dont lie it represents a kind of unconscious myopia 
friedan now heads women men and media a research foundation 
that reports on womens representation in the newspaper magazine 
broadcast and film industries 
the organizations reports have found that few newspaper 
publishers are women and that network television correspondents 
overwhelming tend to be men 
friedan calls the small number of female media executives a 
symbolic annihilation of women 
the figures she said speak for themselves you cant measure 
what doesnt exist 
of the 555 television characters surveyed in the women in film 
study with few notable exceptions most female roles perpetuated 
male fantasies of halfclad halfbrained women who needed to be 
rescued 
i would say that getting raped or being in jeopardy is 
probably the no 2 or no 3 job on television and in films today 
said linda bloodworththomason whose hit show designing women 
was one of a handful cited in the report as providing realistic 
depictions of women 
im so tired of women being depicted as mindless and 
unadventurous whining and victimized bloodworththomason said 
im embarrassed for my sex 
designing women chronicles the lives of the sugarbaker 
sisters and their two female colleagues who own their own interior 
design company in atlanta none of the women is mindless 
unadventurous or victimized 
not one has to have a man to be happy bloodworththomason 
said they talk about newsweek and rock lyrics and bad doctors 
they talk about the same things that men talk about 
bloodworththomason who with her husband harry thomason also 
produces evening shade the new cbs series starring burt 
reynolds marilu henner and hal holbrook was asked why there 
arent more women directing producing and writing for television 
i dont know she replied there is a good ol boys 
network you have to have something that they want so bad you can 
penetrate the network 
the programming chiefs of nbc cbs abc and the fox broadcasting 
co all are men none would comment for this story 
besides designing women the report lauded murphy brown 
and its acerbic title character played by candice bergen and 
china beach and its lead character the multifaceted nurse 
colleen mcmurphy played by dana delany 
john sacret young executive producer and cocreator of china 
beach called the reports statistics pretty shocking 
but he added in the 60s and 70s women were making great 
strides there was a door that was open very wide our society is 
now wrestling with a conservative leaning that has helped make that 
opening smaller 
loring of mgmpathe wonders if the whole problem of 
discrimination television or no might not be moot today if 
society was better at teaching equality than jumping up and down 
about it 
if in the last 10 years we had spent more time educating our 
children that girls can throw footballs too i dont think 
wed be in the shape were in today she said 
she also wonders why she doesnt hear more from women who want 
an equal opportunity in television 
out of the hundreds of writers who pitch to me maybe 5 
percent are women you tell me why when theres a woman president 
of a major television division why are those women not calling 
here to pitch to me i have had one call this entire season about a 
female director to maybe 250 calls about men directors 
the women who have attained power in the land of television say 
they probably didnt experience overt discrimination because they 
are not the types to be silent about it 
there are things i wont accept as a human being and i wont 
accept that loring said 
so she has never felt that her sex was a problem 
loring laughed i think my insolence and arrogance is worse 
she replied 
suzanne depasse the emmywinning executive producer of 
lonesome dove and president of gordydepasse productions 
formerly motown productions calls herself the ultimate 
hyphenate 
i will always be defined as a black woman producer said 
depasse it has been my experience that there is only one true 
way to have any impact and that is to do good work 
being militant about equal representation is not the answer 
depasse said neither is getting angry 
the only way to get more women into high positions is to let 
your good work speak for itself and to help other women on the way 
said depasse echoing statements made by the other female 
executives 
as much as i hate it im not willing to chuck my career in 
the porcelain receptacle to call attention to something thats 
obvious depasse said 
i can do far more in the position that im in than if i go 
burn a cross on the door of walt disney studios 
