<TEXT>
zhang yueliang set out from qufu in northeastern 
china with five tons of fresh grapes in his truck by the time he 
reached his destination 550 miles down the coast hed lost the 
grapes and nearly his shirt 
all along the way he found roadblocks set up by local 
governments charging for the right to pass he handed over his 
cash a tarpaulin finally grapes when zhang reached the buyer 
five days late the remaining grapes were rotten 
the peoples daily told zhangs story and quoted him as saying 
if they dont get the roadblocks under control no one will dare 
work in transport 
beijing once could have solved the problem with an edict 
prohibiting such local customs barriers today regional conflicts 
are too strong and the central governments moral and economic 
power has eroded 
as national leaders try to develop an economic plan to lead the 
country into the 21st century they are forced to consider not just 
what will work or be ideologically correct but what strong special 
interests will accept 
the one man who used to keep everyone working together 
86yearold deng xiaoping has lost prestige since endorsing the 
army attack on prodemocracy demonstrators last year his public 
appearances are rarer than ever and appeals to his authority 
appear to have little effect 
nothing illustrates the leadership vacuum better than the 
governments inability to produce new five and tenyear plans the 
basic blueprints of chinas economy the current plans expire dec 
31 
premier li peng has said the central committee of the ruling 
communist party will meet before years end to discuss new plans 
before that the party wants a consensus among provincial and 
central officials on spending priorities new development projects 
and economic reforms drafts have been circulated and meetings 
held but there are few signs of progress 
provincial governments are competing for state aid and other 
favors 
i suggest that all keep a clear head li told one gathering 
of provincial officials after apparently being besieged by 
petitions for new development zones 
all five existing special economic zones areas of capitalist 
experimentation and technological growth are along the coast and 
western provinces want a share they also seek higher prices for 
their coal iron and other raw materials which are sold to eastern 
factories at discount rates 
an influential government economist ma hong publicly endorsed 
the western provinces plea last week and advocated giving the 
region more freedom to experiment that indicates a deal may have 
been struck 
there has been no agreement to get rid of the provincial customs 
barriers which went up in the past year as regional officials 
tried to reserve their markets for local products during a 
nationwide decline in consumption 
conflicting regional interests are not the only fragmenting 
force officials with opposing ideological positions are struggling 
for personal power and control of chinas future 
most unusual is the inclusion of widely divergent views in the 
official media which generally stress uniformity 
leading economists who met this month were quoted as advocating 
such radical reforms as turning state factories over to public 
shareholders and letting the market determine most prices 
conservatives who halted the momentum of reform two years ago 
want two more years of slow growth but are mindful of communisms 
collapse elsewhere and concede some reform is needed to save china 
from a similar fate 
without reform it is impossible to show communisms 
superiority and increase its attractiveness said government 
spokesman yuan mu a leading conservative 
he said the market must play a role but that state planning and 
ownership should remain dominant 
that was the idea 10 years ago when deng first grafted limited 
free markets and private enterprise onto chinas planned economy 
the free market was to be a supplement 
in practice the unplanned sector has flourished while the 
favored state sector has wilted 
fewer than onethird of state factories will make a profit this 
year and the government will pay 115 billion to bail out the 
rest according to official figures 
factories outside the state plan including private ones and 
those set up by villages and towns now produce half the gross 
national product 
a western diplomat in beijing said the era of planners may be 
over 
the economy has become so complex she said on condition of 
anonymity the information revolution has overtaken china to 
say nothing of the need for speedy product development a planned 
economy cant react quickly enough 
perhaps deng has recognized this 
recently he called for better more rapid and more 
effective reforms his remarks were made public by a leading 
economic official chen jinhua but received only passing notice 
and seemed to have no impact on the fiveyear plan debate 
in the words of a western banker who deals with leading chinese 
economists the battle is continuing im not at all clear that 
we will have anything released except platitudes for a good 
while 
