<TEXT>
treasury secretary nicholas f brady broke his 
public silence on the socalled credit crunch with a plea to 
regulators to soften their crackdown on bank lending 
be mindful of the effect your behavior can have on the 
willingness of banks to take even the reasonable risk of lending to 
good credits brady said tuesday in remarks directed at the 
nations bank examiners 
we need a banking system that is a taker not a shedder of 
such risks he said 
a text of the speech delivered to the arthritis foundation in 
new york was released in washington brady also signaled that the 
administration wants the dollar to stop falling 
his comments on the credit crunch come amid growing concern that 
banks reluctance to lend is holding back an already weak economy 
president bush conducted a series of meetings last week 
discussing the economic lull with top advisers senior regulators 
and business executives 
bankers and some business owners have complained for nearly a 
year that regulators were cracking down too hard in the wake of the 
savings and loan debacle 
regulators responded that they were simply urging prudence in 
response to more fragile economic conditions particularly in the 
commercial real estate industry 
brady conceded that traditional lending standards applied by 
many banks clearly eroded during the long economic expansion of 
the 1980s 
but he cautioned to the regulators id like to say publicly 
what ive said privately many times use some judgment apply some 
balance dont use unrealistically negative scenarios in evaluating 
loans dont overreact 
a federal reserve survey of lending officers released monday 
found that bankers were becoming increasingly cautious about making 
loans not only to commercial real estate developers but also to 
large corporations and home buyers two types of borrowers 
generally considered safe 
let me offer a word to banks brady said i urge you to 
keep lending to your good customers lets not overreact to the 
economy or to the regulators 
your franchise depends upon your continued willingness to 
stand by your customers i urge you not to walk away from those 
whose trust you have worked so hard to earn 
some banks have come under pressure to cut back lending by the 
need to meet stricter capital standards taking effect in january 
under an international agreement but brady said banks had 
alternatives including cutting costs reducing dividends or 
seeking a merger partner 
brady also sought to calm fears about the condition of the 
banking industry saying the banks of 1990 are not the sampls of 
the 1980s they are as different as chalk and cheese 
he said banks have a capital cushion of 200 billion to absorb 
losses 6 percent of their assets compared with 10 billion for 
sampls in 1987 or 1 percent of their assets 
regarding the dollar brady said the deficit reductions in the 
