<TEXT>
guinness plc said wednesday it has agreed to buy 
spains largest brewer la cruz del campo for 102 billion in a 
deal that will make the british company the worlds 12th largest 
brewer 
the acquisition would be one of the biggest foreign takeovers in 
spain where closely held cruz del campo commands a 22 percent 
share of the fastgrowing beer market 
guinness which ranks 17th among the worlds brewers said it 
already had the backing of shareholders who control more than half 
the sevillebased companys stock 
guinness said it also has reached an agreement with the stroh 
brewery co of detroit to buy both its 28 percent holding in cruz 
del campo and its 30 percent holding in henninger espanola sa a 
cruz del campo subsidiary the purchase price of the henninger 
stake is 18 million pounds or 355 million 
the acquisition of cruzcampo provides guinness with a key 
strategic base in spain said guinness chairman anthony tennant 
the decision to sell the group has not been an easy one but 
we reached the conclusion earlier this year that cruz del campo 
had reached the limits of what it could achieve on its own said 
cruz del campo chairman ignacio ybarra mendaro 
the spanish brewer whose shares are not publicly traded was on 
the block for nearly a year and had attracted interest from a 
variety of foreign brewers 
guinness said it would pay for the acquisition with cash and 
existing credit lines it said the purchase was not expected to 
dilute its earnings per share in the first year after the deal is 
completed the purchase subsequently should enhance earnings 
guinness said 
the deal is expected to be completed in january 1991 
philip morrisey an analyst with the london investment firm 
kleinwort benson securities said the acquisition would help 
balance guinness income from brewing and distilling morrisey 
estimated that adding cruz del campo would raise brewing results 
from 17 percent to about 21 percent of guinness pretax profit 
but analysts questioned whether cruz del campo would be able to 
continue expanding at its current rate industry projections called 
for a slowdown in the growth of spanish beer sales to about 1 
percent this year from the 4 percent average of the 1980s 
analysts said nationwide expansion could be difficult because of 
strongholds that other brewers have in regions outside andalucia 
where cruz del campo dominates 
spaniards are loyal to regional brands and it wont be easy to 
