<DOCNO> AP901121-0253 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
michael r milken climbed quietly to the 
pinnacle of highfinance in the 1980s he descended with a 
shattering crash into disgrace and prison where hell likely spend 
a good chunk of the 1990s 
born and raised in california milken was a math whiz helping 
his fathers accounting business by age 10 he studied arcane 
business tracts while others marched for civil rights and peace 
during the 1960s in his early years on wall street milken 
digested financial documents during a twohour commute 
with the same passion milken avoided the limelight after 
gaining market prowess shunning interviews and refusing to pose 
alone for the annual report of his employer drexel burnham lambert 
inc 
milken became a familiar figure only after speculator ivan 
boesky fingered him in the governments fraud investigation in late 
1986 the most prominent financier in the securities industry in 
the booming 1980s milken became prosecutors main target 
after insisting he was innocent milken changed his mind in 
april under a plea bargain he pleaded guilty to six felony counts 
and agreed to pay 600 million in penalties and restitution to 
defrauded investors 
the 44yearold former head of drexels junkbond department was 
sentenced wednesday to a 10year imprisonment and three years of 
probation he must serve at least a third of the prison term 
to some it might sound ironic but i have spent a lifetime 
trying to avoid publicity milken wrote in letter to us 
district judge kimba wood prior to sentencing my parents taught 
me if you worked hard and knew you did a good job you should not 
need recognition from others 
milken was born on the fourth of july in 1946 as a child he was 
a star student and said he was embarrassed when his fourthgrade 
teacher singled out his perfect scores 
he graduated the university of california at berkeley in 1968 
and went on to the university of pennsylvanias prestigious wharton 
school in between he married lori anne hackel his high school 
sweetheart 
in 1970 at age 24 milken joined drexels new york office as 
head of fixedincome research commuting from his southern new 
jersey home by bus by 1973 he was head of highyield bonds his 
compensation was set in a 1975 formula and never altered that 
gave him a portion of the departments profits 
milken was to become infamous for the 11 billion he earned 
from 198387 550 million in 1987 alone milken has said the 
wealth was a byproduct of his work raising money for companies 
i went to wall street with the desire to help change society 
for the better not to find a fortune milken told the judge 
i felt that working in the financial community created the 
best opportunity for social change making capital available where 
it hadnt been before he wrote 
prompted by his fathers illness milken was allowed to move 
drexels highyield bond department to beverly hills calif in 
1978 as the economy prospered in the mid1980s wall street and 
junk bonds developed into a 200 billion market by the decades 
end 
they were used in the biggest takeover deals ever helping to 
reshape american business and creating an inner circle of corporate 
raiders milken became linked to the mock title of drexels annual 
junk bond conference the predators ball 
he worked 18 hour days and scheduled 4 am meetings with 
corporate executives soliciting his financial acumen he and his 
lawyers maintain milken still had time for a quiet home life with 
his wife and three children in a modest house 10 blocks from the 
encino calif home his parents bought in 1954 
in his letter to the judge milken said of his ordeal i have 
been forced to face the challenge that not only am i portrayed as a 
fraud but everything my life stood for is called a fraud and all 
the principles i have spoken about my whole life are hollow 
