<TEXT>
here are short profiles of some of the major 
figures in wall streets financial scandals besides michael milken 
michael r milken former head of junkbond trading at drexel 
burnham lambert inc sentenced to a 10 year imprisonment and three 
years probation on six counts of violating federal securities and 
tax laws he also agreed to pay 600 million in penalties four of 
the six charges involved dealings with chief accuser ivan f 
boesky though none in insider trading or racketeering milken is 
widely regarded as the most powerful financier of the 1980s 
ivan boesky former speculator in takeover stocks paid 100 
million and pleaded guilty to one count of lying to federal 
regulators in a broad insider trading network he was released from 
federal custody in april after completing two years of a threeyear 
prison term his confessions in late 1986 led investigators to 
milken 
dennis levine paroled last year after serving 17 months of a 
twoyear prison term for securities fraud tax evasion and perjury 
levines confessions about a broad insider trading ring led 
prosecutors to boesky the former drexel managing director who 
accepted satchels of money and arranged deals from pay phones 
pleaded guilty to four felonies and returned 116 million in 
alleged illegal profits in a firstperson article in a business 
magazine this year levine said he started an investment advisory 
firm 
martin siegel pleaded guilty in 1987 to illegal stock trading 
and tax evasion while head of mergers and acquisitions at kidder 
peabody amp co he also agreed to return 9 million in cash and 
securities to settle civil charges for his role in illegal dealings 
with boesky siegel a former drexel managing director was 
sentenced in june to a twomonth prison term which he has 
completed 
boyd l jefferies a los angeles stockbroker snared in the 
boesky web was placed on probation and fined 250000 after two 
years of helping the government he pleaded guilty to two felony 
counts in 1987 and then testified in the trials of gaf corp and 
corporate raider paul bilzerian he is living and working in palm 
springs calif and aspen colo 
paul a bilzerian the florida investor last year received 
four years in prison for his conviction on nine counts of 
securities fraud conspiracy and making false statements and fined 
15 million the sentence for the former singer co chairman was 
the stiffest in the wall street scandals bilzerian is is free 
pending appeal 
robert freeman former head of arbitrage for goldman sachs amp 
co was arrested along with two other executives for insider 
trading in the most dramatic of the governments string of cases 
implicated by siegel freeman pleaded guilty to one felony count 
and in april was sentenced to four months in prison and fined 1 
million he completed the term aug 30 
bruce newberg a former drexel trader was indicted along with 
milken and convicted with five others in the princetonnewport 
partners racketeering and fraud trial he was sentenced to three 
months in prison in the princetonnewport case newberg was 
milkens assistant at drexels beverly hills calif highyield 
bond division his status in the milken case is unresolved 
john a mulheren jr a former wunderkind stock speculator was 
convicted earlier this year of conspiracy and securities fraud in 
connection for manipulating gulf amp western inc stock at boeskys 
behest in 1985 mulheren was sentenced this month to one year and 
one day in prison and fined 186 million hes free pending 
appeal 
