<TEXT>
kimba m wood the rookie federal judge who gave 
michael r milken a 10year prison term wednesday lived up to her 
reputation 
friends and acquaintances of wood said the judges handling of 
the most explosive case in her short tenure on the manhattan 
federal bench was characteristically thorough and precise 
i think she went through the most searching careful and 
methodical and thoughtful process said lloyd constantine head 
of antitrust enforcement for new york state and a friend of wood 
she did not treat the matter lightly constantine said i 
cant recall a sentencing where a judge invested so much time and 
effort 
wood was besieged with hundreds of letters from milken 
supporters and critics alike she blazed through mountains of legal 
documents from thedefense and prosecution one portraying milken 
as a gentle philanthropist the other painting him as an arrogant 
crook it was clear she believed neither 
perhaps most important acquaintances said was the 
extraordinary hearing wood convened last month into unproven 
allegations of milkens wrongdoing beyond the six felonies he 
admitted it showed both her skepticism and desire to leave no 
question unresolved in her final reckoning of milkens fate 
laura handman a manhattan attorney and another friend of wood 
said she felt confident the judge reviewed all the evidence and 
weighed all the considerations very closely in reaching her 
decision 
wood 46 is the youngest judge on the manhattan federal bench 
one of the busiest in the nation she was appointed two years ago 
and received milkens case through the courts random assignment 
system 
she had no prior sentencing history in major criminal cases 
leaving legal experts little on which to speculate few anticipated 
shed give milken 10 years of the maximum 28 he faced 
the severity of the term more than triple the time given 
milkens chief accuser ivan f boesky was seen as a strong message 
to the financial community that securitieslaw abusers will be 
dealt with severely 
people familiar with wood have described her as a sensitive 
hardworking judge whose quiet demeanor and dark good looks belie a 
sharp mind and a gift for remembering detail even her husband 
time magazine journalist michael kramer recently described woods 
appearance as misleading to the unwary 
shes always had this very calm exterior and yet shes very 
tough kramer said i mean in the judicial sense in a 
steeltrap mind way 
the few nationally prominent cases wood handled prior to the 
milken case suggested she was willing to be bold 
in october 1988 she reversed a ruling by the immigration and 
naturalization service that had denied refugee status to a ghanian 
soldier who plotted a coup against his government last year she 
upheld the right of a 76yearold new york state judge to seek 
reappointment although he had passed retirement age 
wood was born jan 2 1944 in port townsend wash her parents 
decided to name her kimba after a small town in south australias 
eyre peninsula theyd found on a map 
she attended the sorbonne in paris got her ba from 
connecticut college masters degree from the london school of 
economics and law degree from harvard university before she became 
a federal judge she practiced antitrust law in washington and new 
york 
</TEXT>
