<TEXT>
a pittsburghbased drug maker sued 
american cyanamid co for allegedly violating a marketing agreement 
on a drug used to treat high blood pressure 
mylan pharmaceuticals inc is seeking 239 million from american 
cyanamid for allegedly failing to exercise its best efforts 
to advertise promote and market the drug maxzide from 1987 
through this year 
the suit also seeks at least 176 million from american cyanamid 
for failing to try hard enough to launch an improved version of 
maxzide 
in addition the suit seeks 100 million for american cyanamids 
alleged promotion of its other hypertensive products as well as 
royalties 500 million in punitive damages and the exclusive right 
to market the drug and the bowtie shape of maxzide tablets 
the suit says american cyanamid agreed to introduce and sell 
maxzide through its lederle laboratories division in march 1984 on 
mylans request 
mylan a major generic drug manufacturer developed the drug in 
the early 1980s to compete with other potassiumsaving 
hypertensive medications the company said in the suit filed 
tuesday in us district court in clarksburg 
american cyanamid based in wayne nj has paid mylan 361 
million in royalties on maxzide products since 1988 on net sales of 
2124 million the lawsuit said 
jeff hoyak a lederle spokesman said the company hadnt seen 
the lawsuit and declined comment 
