<TEXT>
law enforcers praised the 10year prison term 
given to michael r milken on wednesday but some legal experts 
said it was unusually stiff and the financiers supporters called 
the punishment excessively brutal 
from washington to wall street to the west coast where milken 
made his home the sentence provoked the kind of mixed reaction 
that underscored the widely divergent public opinion of the famous 
junkbond pioneer 
milken former head of drexel burnham lambert incs highyield 
bond division was sentenced by us district judge kimba wood for 
six felonies stemming from his role as a powerful investment banker 
of the past decade 
outstanding richly deserved said bruce baird a former 
assistant us attorney who led the initial stages of the 
prosecution i think judge wood is sending a message to wall 
street that its time to stop mewing about technical offenses and 
time to start obeying the law 
attorney general dick thornburgh praised the sentence milken 
received as both fair and appropriate to the circumstances 
former securities and exchange commission chairman david s 
ruder said he was pleased and surprised i did not expect it to 
be that severe but i think the penalty is quite in accord with the 
severity of his conduct 
some lawmakers though said that the sentence no matter how 
severe could not undo what they called the damage brought by 
milkens crimes 
the harsh fact of the matter is that it will take the american 
public much longer than 10 years and much more than 600 million to 
pay for the mess these financial engineering schemes have left 
behind said rep john dingell dmich chairman of the house 
energy and commerce committee which oversees the sec 
on the other hand some legal experts said the sentences 
severity while justified seemed to outstrip the nature of 
milkens crimes 
i think the sentence is all symbolic its got nothing to do 
with the need to protect society from any future threats from 
milken said arthur mathews the lawyer for takeover speculator 
paul a bilzerian who received what had been the stiffest sentence 
in the wall street fraud scandal four years before wood 
announced milkens fate 
implicit in the sentence is that this was more than an 
aberration in her view and this was systemic he said 
there was also little sympathy on wall street where nearly 
everyone has a friend who has been laid off as a result of the 
downturn in the financial markets since the stock market crash 
three years ago 
when th sentence was handed down shortly before noon a loud 
commotion could be heard for about five seconds on the floor of the 
new york stock exchange brokers said similar to the reaction 
when a stock price takes a quick dive 
it was nothing like a wild panic the damage is done already 
and weve all got to go on from here said steven schaeffer a 
floor broker with lawrence helfant hopefully hes the last of 
the yuppies to go 
frank kettles 31 a wall street telecommunications worker 
learned of milkens sentence while drinking with a friend at 
houlihans bar in manhattans downtown financial district 
yeah he shouted raising his fist wall street got a bad 
name because of people like him 
down the block kecia montgomery 25 a former drexel worker who 
quit two years to become a nurse because the profession is about 
caring not taking took time out from chatting with a hotdog 
vendor to say that milkens sentence inspires little sympathy with 
her 
if you cant do the time dont do the crime said 
montgomery its not fair that he did his dirty work and hurt a 
lot of people 
but in greater los angeles where milken lives and used to work 
many of his friends reacted with dismay and outrage 
its like they hit me over the head with a sledgehammer what 
a waste of talent said richard riordan a prominent lawyer and 
philanthropist who has been an ally of milken in many business and 
charitable activities 
</TEXT>
